library("tidyverse")
surveys_complete <- read_csv("data/surveys_complete.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   record_id = col_double(),
##   month = col_double(),
##   day = col_double(),
##   year = col_double(),
##   plot_id = col_double(),
##   species_id = col_character(),
##   sex = col_character(),
##   hindfoot_length = col_double(),
##   weight = col_double(),
##   genus = col_character(),
##   species = col_character(),
##   taxa = col_character(),
##   plot_type = col_character()
## )
ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) + geom_point()

surveys_plot <- ggplot(data = surveys_complete, 
                       mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length))

surveys_plot + 
    geom_point()

#install.packages("hexbin")
library("hexbin")

Challenge (optional)

surveys_plot +
  geom_hex()

* Strengths: shows density of points in different areas of graph when there is overplotting of points, weaknesses: you cannot see all the spaces between points in areas on graph where there is not a lot of overlap

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1)

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1, color = "blue")

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1, aes(color = species_id))

Challenge

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = plot_type))

* This isnt a good way to show the data, scatter plots are meant to show continuous data but species_id is a concrete variable, so the data is broken up into separate columns and its difficult to interpret the data. It would be better to use a boxplot.

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, color = "tomato")

* To put boxplot in front of points so that its not hidden, put geom_jitter() before geom_boxplot()

Challenge

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_violin()

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_violin() +
    scale_y_log10()

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = plot_id)) +
  geom_boxplot()

new_plot_id <- factor(surveys_complete$plot_id)

ggplot(data = surveys_complete, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = new_plot_id)) +
  geom_boxplot()

  • When plot_id is an interger, the color of the data points are on a gradient scale where 1 is the lightest shade and 24 is the darkest shade. When plot_id is a factor, each plot_id number is assigned a different color because they are treated as separate levels.
